KARDIA LEXICON

**Stream 3 — Verse Index (Layer 3)**

**Purpose: **Build a translation-independent word-position index that tags every word in the original-language text with its Strong's ID. The app resolves these tags to English at render time using interlinear alignment data — the verse index itself contains no translation property.

## **1. The No-Translation Principle**

The verse index is the architectural decision that keeps the Kardia Lexicon translation-independent. By tagging word positions in the original-language text (BHS for OT, NA28 for NT) and resolving to English only at render time, the same lexicon works equally well with KJV, ESV, NIV, NASB, or any future translation.

**Critical constraint: **The verse index MUST NOT contain a translation property at any level. If a translation string appears in a pull request touching verse-index.json, the PR is rejected. Translation resolution is the app's responsibility, not the lexicon's.

## **2. Source Texts**

| **Testament** | **Source text** | **Edition** | **Strong****'****s alignment source** | **License** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Old Testament | Biblia Hebraica Stuttgartensia (BHS) | 5th ed. | OpenScriptures Hebrew Bible (OSHB) | CC BY 4.0 |
| New Testament | Nestle-Aland 28 (NA28) | 28th ed. | MorphGNT / SBLGNT Strong's | CC BY-SA 3.0 |
| Deuterocanon (opt.) | Septuagint (Rahlfs) | Rahlfs-Hanhart | LXX Strong's extended | Public domain |

**Note on NA28 vs SBLGNT: **SBLGNT has the most complete freely-licensed Strong's alignment. NA28 is the scholarly standard. Where they diverge on word order or variant readings, NA28 takes precedence for verse position, and the SBLGNT alignment is used for the Strong's ID assignment, with a note flag in the entry.

## **3. Entry Format**

Each verse index entry represents one verse of the original-language text:

| **Field** | **Type** | **Required** | **Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| osisRef | string | Yes | OSIS reference, e.g. Gen.1.1 — do not use human-readable format |
| sourceText | string enum | Yes | "BHS" │ "NA28" │ "LXX" |
| words | array | Yes | One entry per original-language word in verse order |
| words[].position | integer | Yes | Zero-indexed position in original-language verse |
| words[].strongsId | string | Yes | H or G prefix + number |
| words[].morphology | string | Optional | OpenScriptures morphology code (e.g. HVqp3ms) |
| words[].categoryId | string | Optional | Pre-resolved category ID for query performance |
| words[].contextRuleApplied | string | Optional | ID of context rule used if polysemy override applied |
| words[].lemma | string | Optional | Original-script lemma — aids human review |

## **4. Interlinear Alignment Data**

The app resolves verse index tags to English words using interlinear alignment data. This is a separate data layer (not part of the lexicon) that maps original-language word positions to English translation word positions for each supported translation. The lexicon project does not own this data but must document the interface contract.

### **4.1 Interface contract**

The app must be able to call an alignment resolver with the following inputs:

- osisRef (string) — the verse reference

- position (integer) — the original-language word position

- translationId (string) — e.g. "ESV", "KJV", "NIV"

And receive:

- englishWords (array of string) — the English word(s) that render this original-language word in the target translation

- englishPositions (array of integer) — positions in the English verse

**Note: **The alignment resolver is outside the scope of the Kardia Lexicon project itself. The lexicon specifies the contract; implementations are provided by integrators. The open-source release will include a reference implementation against the OSHB interlinear alignment data for ESV and KJV.

## **5. Build Process**

The verse index is generated by a build script, not hand-authored. The build script:

- Reads the source text (BHS / NA28) word by word

- Looks up the Strong's ID for each word from the alignment source

- Validates that the Strong's ID exists in the lexeme map (lexeme-map.json)

- Optionally pre-resolves the categoryId by looking up the Strong's ID in the lexeme map

- Outputs a JSON array sorted by OSIS reference (canonical biblical order)

- Runs the verse-index JSON Schema validator

**Build command: **npm run build:verse-index -- --sourceText BHS --preResolve true

## **6. Scope and Phasing**

| **Phase** | **Scope** | **Word count (approx.)** | **Dependency** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Phase 1 | All verses containing seed category words (30 categories) | ~15,000 verse entries | Seed lexeme map complete |
| Phase 2 | Full Old Testament (BHS) | ~300,000 word entries | Phase 2 lexeme map (OT complete) |
| Phase 3 | Full New Testament (NA28) | ~140,000 word entries | Phase 2 lexeme map (NT complete) |
| Phase 4 (opt.) | Deuterocanon (LXX) | ~80,000 word entries | Extended lexeme map |

## **7. File Size and Delivery**

A full verse index for OT + NT will be large (estimated 80–120 MB uncompressed). The distribution strategy:

- Full JSON file for server-side / build-time use

- NDJSON (newline-delimited JSON) format for streaming access

- Split by book (66 files) for CDN delivery and lazy loading

- SQLite version for embedded/mobile use cases

All formats are generated from the canonical JSON source. Only the canonical JSON is version-controlled directly.